class Solution {
    public int compress(char[] chars) {
        int anchor = 0, write = 0;
        for (int read = 0; read < chars.length; read++) {
            if (read + 1 == chars.length || chars[read + 1] != chars[read]) {
                chars[write++] = chars[anchor];
                if (read > anchor) {
                    for (char c : String.valueOf(read - anchor + 1).toCharArray()) {
                        chars[write++] = c;
                    }
                }
                anchor = read + 1;
            }
        }
        return write;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The algorithm uses two pointers, `anchor` and `write`, to track the start of the current character group and the position to write the compressed character, respectively. It iterates through the array, and whenever it encounters a different character or reaches the end, it writes the character and its count (if greater than 1) to the array. The algorithm modifies the input array in-place and returns the new length of the array.

